There are quite a few different methods that can be used for doing this.  The general idea is to come up with a way to model the problem or questions and then to develop some way to generate answers.

One approach is to create a flowchart that identifies the different operations to perform.  In this case, we could have a box for “determine the number of children in the house”, a box for “number of children”, a box for “boys”, a box for “girls”, and a box for “costs” and connect the different boxes with arrows showing the relationships (such as the number of children goes into the “number of children” box, and then the “number of children”, “boys”, and “girls” boxes go into the cost box).  This allows us to see at a very high level how we can do the calculations.  Since each box has its own operations, we may have to do different calculations for the different boxes and this may get confusing.

Another way would be to use a loop instead of a flowchart.  A loop can be thought of as a loop “from here to wherever”.  For each “wherever”, we perform an operation on data.  The idea here is to come up with operations that create an answer based on input.  In general, we often use a loop to iterate multiple times and come up with an accumulated answer by doing a lot of different small operations on data.  These kinds of loops are often found in programming languages where you might use a “for” loop, a “while” loop, or a “for each” loop to iterate and then perform operations.

These are only two examples of ways you can think of to solve any kind of problem.
